// BRN / CEP RN Case Management - Moodle Quiz Bank (10 modules x 3 contact hours + Capstone)
// Generated Moodle MVP implementation artifact. SME review required before production use.
// No PHI; fictional de-identified scenarios only.

$CATEGORY: $course$/BRN/M01

// question: BRN-M01-Q01
::BRN-M01-Q01::
The core purpose of RN case management is to\: {
~Replace the primary physician
=Coordinate and advocate for safe, effective, patient-centered care across settings
~Reduce all costs regardless of quality
~Eliminate documentation
#### RN case management coordinates and advocates for patient-centered care, balancing quality, safety, and resource use.
}

// question: BRN-M01-Q02
::BRN-M01-Q02::
Operating within one's RN scope of practice means the nurse\: {
~Performs any task requested regardless of licensure
=Acts within the legal/professional boundaries defined for registered nurses
~Ignores standards of practice
~Practices medicine independently
#### Scope of practice defines the legal and professional boundaries for RN actions. Confirm jurisdiction specifics with SME/legal.
}

// question: BRN-M01-Q03
::BRN-M01-Q03::
A patient-centered approach in case management means decisions are guided primarily by\: {
~The case manager's convenience
=The patient's needs, goals, values, and informed preferences
~Payer preferences only
~Facility throughput only
#### Patient-centered care centers the patient's needs, goals, and informed preferences.
}

// question: BRN-M01-Q04
::BRN-M01-Q04::
Case managers balance advocacy for the patient with responsible use of resources. {T
#### Case management balances patient advocacy with appropriate stewardship of resources.}

// question: BRN-M01-Q05
::BRN-M01-Q05::
Which best describes the RN case manager's relationship with the interdisciplinary team? {
~Works in isolation
=Collaborates and communicates across disciplines to coordinate care
~Directs physicians' medical orders
~Avoids other team members
#### Case managers collaborate across disciplines to coordinate care.
}

// question: BRN-M01-Q06
::BRN-M01-Q06::
Standards of professional practice and a code of ethics guide the case manager by\: {
~Being optional suggestions
=Providing a framework for accountable, ethical, competent practice
~Replacing clinical judgment entirely
~Limiting patient advocacy
#### Professional standards and ethics frame accountable, competent practice.
}

// question: BRN-M01-Q07
::BRN-M01-Q07::
Scenario\: A case manager is asked by a supervisor to perform a task that appears outside the RN scope of practice. The most appropriate response is to\: {
~Perform it to avoid conflict
=Decline tasks outside the RN scope, clarify the concern, and seek appropriate qualified involvement
~Delegate it to an aide
~Ignore the request entirely without explanation
#### Nurses should not perform tasks outside scope; they clarify and route to the appropriate qualified professional. Confirm scope with SME/legal.
}

// question: BRN-M01-Q08
::BRN-M01-Q08::
Which are core functions of RN case management? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Assessment and care coordination
~%33.33333%Advocacy for the patient
~%-100.0%Practicing outside one's license
~%33.33333%Monitoring and evaluating outcomes
}

// question: BRN-M01-Q09
::BRN-M01-Q09::
In the home health context, the RN case manager often serves as a\: {
~Barrier between patient and team
=Central coordinator linking the patient, providers, and resources
~Replacement for the physician
~Billing-only function
#### In home health, the case manager coordinates among patient, providers, and resources.
}

// question: BRN-M01-Q10
::BRN-M01-Q10::
This program is structured as continuing education measured in\: {
~CEUs
=Contact hours
~Clinical rotations
~Academic credits
#### BRN continuing education is expressed in contact hours, not CEUs.
}

// question: BRN-M01-Q11
::BRN-M01-Q11::
Maintaining competency through continuing education supports safe, current case-management practice. {T
#### Ongoing education maintains competency for safe practice.}

// question: BRN-M01-Q12
::BRN-M01-Q12::
The overall foundation this module establishes is\: {
~Medication prescribing authority
=The role, scope, ethics, and coordinating function of RN case management
~Facility marketing
~Billing codes only
#### The module establishes role, scope, ethics, and coordination foundations.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/BRN/M02

// question: BRN-M02-Q01
::BRN-M02-Q01::
A comprehensive case-management assessment should include\: {
~Only the primary diagnosis
=Physical, functional, psychosocial, environmental, and support-system factors
~Only insurance information
~Only the patient's age
#### Holistic assessment spans physical, functional, psychosocial, environmental, and support factors.
}

// question: BRN-M02-Q02
::BRN-M02-Q02::
During intake, verifying and reconciling key information helps to\: {
~Delay care
=Establish an accurate baseline and reduce errors
~Avoid documentation
~Replace assessment
#### Accurate intake reconciliation establishes a reliable baseline and reduces errors.
}

// question: BRN-M02-Q03
::BRN-M02-Q03::
A patient-centered care plan goal is best written as\: {
~Vague and open-ended
=Specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, and time-bound, reflecting the patient's priorities
~Decided without the patient
~Focused only on facility metrics
#### SMART, patient-aligned goals support measurable, individualized care planning.
}

// question: BRN-M02-Q04
::BRN-M02-Q04::
The patient (and family/caregiver as appropriate) should be involved in developing the care plan. {T
#### Patient/caregiver involvement is central to patient-centered planning.}

// question: BRN-M02-Q05
::BRN-M02-Q05::
Prioritizing problems in a care plan should be guided primarily by\: {
~Alphabetical order
=Acuity, safety, and the patient's goals
~The case manager's preference
~Billing potential
#### Prioritization reflects acuity, safety, and patient goals.
}

// question: BRN-M02-Q06
::BRN-M02-Q06::
Identifying social determinants of health during assessment helps the case manager to\: {
~Ignore barriers
=Recognize barriers (e.g., transportation, housing, food) that affect outcomes and plan accordingly
~Increase costs only
~Avoid referrals
#### Social determinants influence outcomes and should inform planning and referrals.
}

// question: BRN-M02-Q07
::BRN-M02-Q07::
Scenario\: A newly admitted home-health patient lives alone, has limited mobility, and no nearby support. The case manager should\: {
~Proceed with a standard plan ignoring the situation
=Assess safety and support needs, incorporate resources/referrals (e.g., home support, equipment), and tailor the care plan
~Discharge from services
~Tell the patient to manage alone
#### Assessment of safety/support and resource integration produces an individualized, safe plan.
}

// question: BRN-M02-Q08
::BRN-M02-Q08::
Which belong in a patient-centered care plan? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Measurable goals
~%33.33333%Interventions matched to needs
~%-100.0%Goals decided without the patient
~%33.33333%A plan for evaluation/reassessment
}

// question: BRN-M02-Q09
::BRN-M02-Q09::
Reassessment of the care plan should occur\: {
~Never
=Regularly and when the patient's condition or circumstances change
~Only at discharge
~Only if the payer asks
#### Care plans are living documents reassessed regularly and on change.
}

// question: BRN-M02-Q10
::BRN-M02-Q10::
Using validated assessment tools when appropriate helps to\: {
~Introduce bias
=Support consistent, evidence-informed assessment
~Replace clinical judgment entirely
~Avoid documentation
#### Validated tools support consistency and complement clinical judgment.
}

// question: BRN-M02-Q11
::BRN-M02-Q11::
An accurate, current problem list helps the team deliver coordinated, individualized care. {T
#### A current problem list supports coordinated, individualized care.}

// question: BRN-M02-Q12
::BRN-M02-Q12::
The overall aim of this module is to\: {
~Teach prescribing
=Strengthen comprehensive assessment, intake, and patient-centered care planning
~Replace the physician
~Focus only on billing
#### The aim is sound assessment, intake, and patient-centered planning.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/BRN/M03

// question: BRN-M03-Q01
::BRN-M03-Q01::
Care coordination across disciplines primarily aims to\: {
~Create silos
=Align team members and services so care is safe, continuous, and non-duplicative
~Increase fragmentation
~Reduce communication
#### Coordination aligns the team to deliver safe, continuous, non-duplicative care.
}

// question: BRN-M03-Q02
::BRN-M03-Q02::
Effective interdisciplinary communication is supported by\: {
~Ambiguous handoffs
=Structured, clear, and timely information sharing (e.g., standardized handoff)
~Withholding information
~Relying on memory only
#### Structured, timely communication (e.g., standardized handoffs) reduces errors.
}

// question: BRN-M03-Q03
::BRN-M03-Q03::
When coordinating across settings (hospital, home, community), the case manager should ensure\: {
~Information is lost between settings
=Continuity of the care plan and accurate information transfer
~Each setting starts from scratch
~No follow-up
#### Continuity and accurate transfer prevent gaps across settings.
}

// question: BRN-M03-Q04
::BRN-M03-Q04::
Clear role definition among team members reduces gaps and duplication in care. {T
#### Defined roles reduce gaps and duplication.}

// question: BRN-M03-Q05
::BRN-M03-Q05::
A primary risk when care is poorly coordinated is\: {
~Improved outcomes
=Fragmented care, errors, duplicated services, and gaps
~Lower costs always
~Better communication
#### Poor coordination causes fragmentation, errors, duplication, and gaps.
}

// question: BRN-M03-Q06
::BRN-M03-Q06::
Coordinating referrals effectively includes\: {
~Sending incomplete information
=Providing relevant information, confirming receipt, and following up on outcomes
~Never following up
~Avoiding documentation
#### Effective referrals include complete information, confirmation, and follow-up.
}

// question: BRN-M03-Q07
::BRN-M03-Q07::
Scenario\: A patient is receiving conflicting instructions from two providers. The case manager should\: {
~Pick one at random
=Facilitate communication among the providers to reconcile the plan and clarify instructions for the patient
~Tell the patient to choose
~Ignore the conflict
#### The case manager facilitates reconciliation and clear, consistent instructions.
}

// question: BRN-M03-Q08
::BRN-M03-Q08::
Which support effective care coordination? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Timely, structured communication
~%33.33333%Shared, current care plan
~%-100.0%Withholding information from the team
~%33.33333%Clear roles and follow-up
}

// question: BRN-M03-Q09
::BRN-M03-Q09::
The patient's role in care coordination is best described as\: {
~Passive bystander
=An active partner whose input and understanding are essential
~Irrelevant
~Decision-maker for the clinical team
#### Patients are active partners in coordinated care.
}

// question: BRN-M03-Q10
::BRN-M03-Q10::
Documenting coordination activities (calls, referrals, follow-ups) is important because it\: {
~Wastes time
=Creates a record of actions, supports continuity, and demonstrates accountability
~Replaces communication
~Is optional
#### Documentation records coordination, supports continuity, and shows accountability.
}

// question: BRN-M03-Q11
::BRN-M03-Q11::
Coordinating with community resources can help address needs that affect health outcomes. {T
#### Community resources help address determinants affecting outcomes.}

// question: BRN-M03-Q12
::BRN-M03-Q12::
The overall aim of this module is to\: {
~Teach prescribing
=Strengthen interdisciplinary and cross-setting care coordination
~Promote fragmented care
~Replace the team
#### The aim is effective interdisciplinary, cross-setting coordination.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/BRN/M04

// question: BRN-M04-Q01
::BRN-M04-Q01::
Legally sound nursing documentation should be\: {
~Vague and delayed
=Accurate, objective, timely, complete, and legible
~Based on assumptions
~Altered after the fact without notation
#### Sound documentation is accurate, objective, timely, complete, and legible.
}

// question: BRN-M04-Q02
::BRN-M04-Q02::
Charting should generally reflect\: {
~What the nurse intended to do
=What was actually assessed, done, and observed, and the patient's response
~Only favorable information
~Opinions about the patient's character
#### Documentation reflects actual assessment, actions, observations, and responses.
}

// question: BRN-M04-Q03
::BRN-M04-Q03::
If an error is made in an electronic record, the appropriate action is to\: {
~Delete the entry so no one sees it
=Correct it per policy using an addendum/correction that preserves the original entry and audit trail
~Ask IT to erase the history
~Leave the error and ignore it
#### Corrections must preserve the original entry and audit trail per policy.
}

// question: BRN-M04-Q04
::BRN-M04-Q04::
The medical record can serve as a legal document and may be used in audits or legal proceedings. {T
#### The record is a legal document used in audits and proceedings.}

// question: BRN-M04-Q05
::BRN-M04-Q05::
'Audit-ready' documentation means records are\: {
~Incomplete and disorganized
=Complete, accurate, and organized so they can withstand review
~Hidden from reviewers
~Written in personal shorthand only
#### Audit-ready records are complete, accurate, and organized for review.
}

// question: BRN-M04-Q06
::BRN-M04-Q06::
Documenting patient education and the patient's response is important because it\: {
~Is unnecessary
=Demonstrates the education occurred and supports safe, coordinated care
~Replaces the care plan
~Hides information
#### Documenting education and response evidences teaching and supports care.
}

// question: BRN-M04-Q07
::BRN-M04-Q07::
Scenario\: A case manager realizes a prior entry omitted an important assessment finding from earlier that day. The best action is to\: {
~Backdate a new entry to the earlier time
=Make a clearly labeled late entry/addendum per policy, with the current date/time and reference to when the event occurred
~Ask a colleague to enter it
~Leave it out to avoid scrutiny
#### A properly labeled late entry maintains integrity; backdating or proxy entry is falsification.
}

// question: BRN-M04-Q08
::BRN-M04-Q08::
Which are characteristics of defensible documentation? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Objective and factual
~%33.33333%Timely
~%-100.0%Altered without notation
~%33.33333%Complete and legible
}

// question: BRN-M04-Q09
::BRN-M04-Q09::
Confidentiality and privacy of records require that information is\: {
~Shared with anyone
=Accessed and disclosed only as authorized and necessary, consistent with privacy law and policy
~Posted publicly
~Discussed openly
#### Access/disclosure is limited to authorized, necessary use under privacy law and policy. Confirm specific privacy requirements with SME/legal.
}

// question: BRN-M04-Q10
::BRN-M04-Q10::
Using approved terminology and avoiding unapproved abbreviations helps to\: {
~Confuse readers
=Reduce misinterpretation and errors
~Make charts longer
~Hide information
#### Standardized terminology reduces misinterpretation and error.
}

// question: BRN-M04-Q11
::BRN-M04-Q11::
Documentation should never be falsified, and care that was not provided should not be charted as done. {T
#### Falsification is prohibited; only actual care is documented.}

// question: BRN-M04-Q12
::BRN-M04-Q12::
The overall aim of this module is to\: {
~Teach prescribing
=Strengthen documentation, legal charting, and audit-ready recordkeeping
~Encourage shortcuts
~Replace the care plan
#### The aim is sound documentation, legal charting, and audit readiness.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/BRN/M05

// question: BRN-M05-Q01
::BRN-M05-Q01::
Informed consent generally requires that the patient\: {
~Signs without understanding
=Receives understandable information about the option, risks, benefits, and alternatives and voluntarily agrees
~Is told only the benefits
~Is pressured to agree
#### Informed consent requires understandable disclosure and voluntary agreement. Confirm legal specifics with SME/legal.
}

// question: BRN-M05-Q02
::BRN-M05-Q02::
Patient advocacy in case management means the nurse\: {
~Always defers to the payer
=Supports the patient's rights, voice, and informed choices within ethical and legal bounds
~Makes all decisions for the patient
~Ignores patient preferences
#### Advocacy supports the patient's rights and informed choices within ethical/legal limits.
}

// question: BRN-M05-Q03
::BRN-M05-Q03::
Respecting patient autonomy means\: {
~Overriding patient decisions
=Honoring the patient's right to make informed decisions about their own care
~Withholding information
~Deciding for the patient
#### Autonomy is the patient's right to make informed decisions.
}

// question: BRN-M05-Q04
::BRN-M05-Q04::
Patients generally have the right to refuse care, and refusals should be documented and addressed appropriately. {T
#### The right to refuse is fundamental; refusals are documented and managed appropriately. Confirm legal nuances with SME/legal.}

// question: BRN-M05-Q05
::BRN-M05-Q05::
A professional boundary issue arises when the nurse\: {
~Maintains a therapeutic, professional relationship
=Allows personal interests or relationships to interfere with professional judgment or the patient relationship
~Documents accurately
~Follows the code of ethics
#### Boundary issues occur when personal interests compromise professional judgment/relationship.
}

// question: BRN-M05-Q06
::BRN-M05-Q06::
When an ethical dilemma arises, a sound approach is to\: {
~Decide quickly alone
=Identify the issue, consider the patient's values and ethical principles, and use available resources (e.g., ethics consultation, policy)
~Ignore it
~Always choose the cheapest option
#### Structured ethical reasoning and available resources support sound decisions.
}

// question: BRN-M05-Q07
::BRN-M05-Q07::
Scenario\: A competent patient declines a recommended service that the team believes is beneficial. The case manager should\: {
~Override the patient's decision
=Ensure the patient is informed of risks/benefits/alternatives, respect the autonomous decision, document it, and continue supportive care
~Discharge the patient for non-compliance
~Pressure the patient to agree
#### A competent, informed patient may refuse; the nurse ensures understanding, respects autonomy, and documents.
}

// question: BRN-M05-Q08
::BRN-M05-Q08::
Which are core ethical principles relevant to case management? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Autonomy
~%33.33333%Beneficence and non-maleficence
~%-100.0%Deception
~%33.33333%Justice
}

// question: BRN-M05-Q09
::BRN-M05-Q09::
Confidentiality of patient information means the nurse should\: {
~Share freely
=Protect information and disclose only as authorized or legally required
~Post about patients
~Discuss patients publicly
#### Confidentiality limits disclosure to authorized/legally required situations.
}

// question: BRN-M05-Q10
::BRN-M05-Q10::
Cultural humility in advocacy means the nurse\: {
~Imposes their own values
=Respects and responds to the patient's cultural beliefs and preferences
~Ignores culture
~Treats all patients identically
#### Cultural humility respects and responds to the patient's beliefs and preferences.
}

// question: BRN-M05-Q11
::BRN-M05-Q11::
Advance directives express a patient's wishes and should be honored within legal and policy frameworks. {T
#### Advance directives guide care per legal and policy frameworks. Confirm specifics with SME/legal.}

// question: BRN-M05-Q12
::BRN-M05-Q12::
The overall aim of this module is to\: {
~Teach prescribing
=Strengthen knowledge of patient rights, consent, advocacy, and ethical boundaries
~Reduce advocacy
~Replace the ethics committee
#### The aim is rights, consent, advocacy, and ethical boundaries.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/BRN/M06

// question: BRN-M06-Q01
::BRN-M06-Q01::
A safe transition of care depends most on\: {
~Speed alone
=Accurate information transfer, a clear plan, and confirmed follow-up arrangements
~Minimizing patient involvement
~Avoiding documentation
#### Safe transitions require accurate information transfer, a clear plan, and confirmed follow-up.
}

// question: BRN-M06-Q02
::BRN-M06-Q02::
Discharge planning should ideally begin\: {
~At the moment of discharge
=Early in the care episode and be updated as the patient's status changes
~After the patient leaves
~Only if problems occur
#### Early, dynamic discharge planning improves outcomes and reduces readmission risk.
}

// question: BRN-M06-Q03
::BRN-M06-Q03::
Medication reconciliation at transitions helps to\: {
~Increase errors
=Identify and resolve discrepancies to prevent medication errors
~Replace the pharmacist
~Avoid documentation
#### Reconciliation identifies discrepancies and reduces medication errors at transitions.
}

// question: BRN-M06-Q04
::BRN-M06-Q04::
Teach-back (having the patient restate instructions in their own words) helps confirm understanding at discharge. {T
#### Teach-back verifies patient understanding of discharge instructions.}

// question: BRN-M06-Q05
::BRN-M06-Q05::
Connecting patients to appropriate community resources helps to\: {
~Create barriers
=Address ongoing needs and support continuity after discharge
~Increase readmissions
~Avoid follow-up
#### Community resources support continuity and address ongoing needs.
}

// question: BRN-M06-Q06
::BRN-M06-Q06::
A key cause of avoidable readmissions is\: {
~Thorough discharge planning
=Poor transitions, unclear instructions, and inadequate follow-up
~Medication reconciliation
~Patient education
#### Poor transitions and follow-up contribute to avoidable readmissions.
}

// question: BRN-M06-Q07
::BRN-M06-Q07::
Scenario\: A patient is being discharged home but expresses confusion about their new medications and follow-up appointments. The case manager should\: {
~Proceed with discharge as planned
=Pause to clarify instructions using teach-back, reconcile medications, confirm follow-up, and arrange support/resources as needed
~Tell the patient to figure it out
~Cancel the discharge entirely
#### Clarifying instructions, reconciling medications, and confirming follow-up create a safe transition.
}

// question: BRN-M06-Q08
::BRN-M06-Q08::
Which elements belong in a safe discharge plan? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Clear instructions the patient understands
~%33.33333%Medication reconciliation
~%-100.0%No follow-up arrangements
~%33.33333%Connection to needed resources/support
}

// question: BRN-M06-Q09
::BRN-M06-Q09::
Involving family/caregivers in discharge planning is helpful because they\: {
~Should be excluded
=Often support follow-through and can identify barriers at home
~Make care less safe
~Replace the care team
#### Caregivers support follow-through and identify home barriers.
}

// question: BRN-M06-Q10
::BRN-M06-Q10::
Communicating the transition plan to the receiving provider/setting should be\: {
~Optional
=Timely, accurate, and complete to ensure continuity
~Vague
~Avoided
#### Timely, accurate, complete communication to the receiving setting ensures continuity.
}

// question: BRN-M06-Q11
::BRN-M06-Q11::
Follow-up after discharge (e.g., confirming appointments or check-in) can reduce gaps and readmissions. {T
#### Post-discharge follow-up reduces gaps and readmissions.}

// question: BRN-M06-Q12
::BRN-M06-Q12::
The overall aim of this module is to\: {
~Teach prescribing
=Strengthen safe transitions, discharge planning, and community-resource linkage
~Increase readmissions
~Replace the discharge team
#### The aim is safe transitions, discharge planning, and resource linkage.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/BRN/M07

// question: BRN-M07-Q01
::BRN-M07-Q01::
Utilization review (UR) in case management primarily evaluates\: {
~Staff schedules
=Whether services are appropriate, necessary, and delivered at the right level of care
~Marketing performance
~Facility decor
#### UR evaluates appropriateness, medical necessity, and level of care.
}

// question: BRN-M07-Q02
::BRN-M07-Q02::
'Medical necessity' generally refers to services that are\: {
~Requested by the patient regardless of need
=Appropriate and required for the patient's condition based on accepted standards
~The most expensive option
~Optional conveniences
#### Medical necessity reflects appropriate, required care per accepted standards. Confirm payer/legal definitions with SME.
}

// question: BRN-M07-Q03
::BRN-M07-Q03::
'Payer-safe' communication means the case manager\: {
~Exaggerates the patient's condition to obtain authorization
=Communicates accurately and truthfully, supported by documentation
~Withholds relevant information
~Guarantees coverage outcomes
#### Payer-safe communication is accurate, truthful, and documentation-supported; never exaggerated or fraudulent.
}

// question: BRN-M07-Q04
::BRN-M07-Q04::
Misrepresenting a patient's condition to obtain authorization is unethical and can constitute fraud. {T
#### Misrepresentation for authorization is unethical and may be fraud.}

// question: BRN-M07-Q05
::BRN-M07-Q05::
Documentation supporting medical necessity should\: {
~Be vague
=Clearly reflect the clinical picture, services, and rationale
~Be inflated
~Be omitted
#### Documentation should accurately support the clinical picture and rationale for services.
}

// question: BRN-M07-Q06
::BRN-M07-Q06::
When a service is denied by a payer, an appropriate case-manager action is to\: {
~Tell the patient nothing
=Understand the reason, support appeal/alternative options as appropriate, and keep the patient informed
~Falsify records to overturn it
~Abandon the patient
#### Case managers address denials through legitimate appeals/alternatives and patient communication.
}

// question: BRN-M07-Q07
::BRN-M07-Q07::
Scenario\: A supervisor pressures the case manager to document a higher level of need than is clinically accurate to secure payment. The case manager should\: {
~Comply to keep peace
=Refuse to misrepresent, document accurately, and escalate the concern through appropriate channels
~Quietly alter the chart
~Ask the patient to lie
#### The nurse must document accurately, refuse misrepresentation, and escalate; this protects patients and integrity.
}

// question: BRN-M07-Q08
::BRN-M07-Q08::
Which practices support ethical utilization management? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Accurate documentation
~%33.33333%Truthful payer communication
~%-100.0%Inflating severity for payment
~%33.33333%Balancing patient advocacy with appropriate resource use
}

// question: BRN-M07-Q09
::BRN-M07-Q09::
Balancing advocacy and stewardship means the case manager\: {
~Always chooses the cheapest option
=Advocates for needed care while using resources responsibly
~Ignores cost entirely
~Ignores patient needs
#### Case managers advocate for appropriate care while stewarding resources responsibly.
}

// question: BRN-M07-Q10
::BRN-M07-Q10::
Knowing the patient's coverage and benefits helps the case manager to\: {
~Deny care
=Plan realistic, appropriate care and reduce surprises for the patient
~Avoid documentation
~Replace clinical judgment
#### Understanding benefits supports realistic, appropriate planning.
}

// question: BRN-M07-Q11
::BRN-M07-Q11::
The patient should be kept informed about coverage issues affecting their care in an honest, understandable way. {T
#### Honest, understandable communication keeps patients informed about coverage issues.}

// question: BRN-M07-Q12
::BRN-M07-Q12::
The overall aim of this module is to\: {
~Teach prescribing
=Strengthen utilization review, medical-necessity documentation, and payer-safe communication
~Encourage upcoding
~Replace the payer
#### The aim is sound UR, medical-necessity documentation, and payer-safe communication.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/BRN/M08

// question: BRN-M08-Q01
::BRN-M08-Q01::
The purpose of quality assurance/quality improvement in case management is to\: {
~Assign blame
=Systematically monitor and improve care processes and outcomes
~Increase paperwork only
~Hide problems
#### QA/QI systematically monitors and improves processes and outcomes.
}

// question: BRN-M08-Q02
::BRN-M08-Q02::
Risk management primarily focuses on\: {
~Ignoring hazards
=Identifying, evaluating, and reducing risks to patients, staff, and the organization
~Increasing risk
~Marketing
#### Risk management identifies and reduces risks to patients, staff, and the organization.
}

// question: BRN-M08-Q03
::BRN-M08-Q03::
An incident report should be\: {
~A way to assign blame
=An objective, factual, timely record of an event used to improve safety
~Optional
~Filled with opinions
#### Incident reports are objective, factual, timely, and used to improve safety, not to assign blame.
}

// question: BRN-M08-Q04
::BRN-M08-Q04::
Near-misses, not just actual harm events, are valuable to report because they reveal system weaknesses. {T
#### Near-miss reporting reveals weaknesses before harm occurs.}

// question: BRN-M08-Q05
::BRN-M08-Q05::
Escalation in case management means\: {
~Hiding a problem
=Promptly raising a concern to the appropriate level/person when it exceeds one's authority or requires urgent attention
~Waiting indefinitely
~Solving everything alone
#### Escalation routes concerns promptly to the right level when needed.
}

// question: BRN-M08-Q06
::BRN-M08-Q06::
A 'just culture' approach to safety emphasizes\: {
~Punishing all errors harshly
=Learning from errors and addressing system factors while maintaining accountability
~Ignoring errors
~Hiding events
#### Just culture balances accountability with learning and system improvement.
}

// question: BRN-M08-Q07
::BRN-M08-Q07::
Scenario\: A case manager identifies a recurring process gap that has led to several near-misses in handoffs. The best action is to\: {
~Ignore it since no one was harmed
=Report it through QA/risk channels, document the pattern, and propose/participate in a process improvement
~Blame an individual colleague
~Conceal it
#### Reporting patterns and improving the process prevents future harm.
}

// question: BRN-M08-Q08
::BRN-M08-Q08::
Which support a strong safety/quality program? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Timely incident and near-miss reporting
~%33.33333%Objective, factual documentation
~%-100.0%Punitive blame for all errors
~%33.33333%Process improvement based on data
}

// question: BRN-M08-Q09
::BRN-M08-Q09::
When a patient-safety concern is urgent and exceeds the case manager's authority, the nurse should\: {
~Wait for the next meeting
=Escalate immediately to the appropriate person/level per policy
~Do nothing
~Document only and move on
#### Urgent concerns require immediate escalation per policy.
}

// question: BRN-M08-Q10
::BRN-M08-Q10::
Tracking and trending data on incidents helps the organization to\: {
~Hide issues
=Identify patterns and target improvements
~Increase errors
~Avoid accountability
#### Trending data reveals patterns and guides targeted improvement.
}

// question: BRN-M08-Q11
::BRN-M08-Q11::
Reporting a safety concern in good faith is part of professional accountability. {T
#### Good-faith reporting is part of professional accountability and safety culture.}

// question: BRN-M08-Q12
::BRN-M08-Q12::
The overall aim of this module is to\: {
~Teach prescribing
=Strengthen quality assurance, risk management, incident reporting, and escalation
~Discourage reporting
~Replace leadership
#### The aim is QA, risk management, incident reporting, and escalation.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/BRN/M09

// question: BRN-M09-Q01
::BRN-M09-Q01::
Chronic disease management in case management emphasizes\: {
~One-time treatment only
=Ongoing support, self-management education, monitoring, and coordination over time
~Avoiding the patient
~Ignoring comorbidities
#### Chronic disease management is longitudinal\: support, education, monitoring, and coordination.
}

// question: BRN-M09-Q02
::BRN-M09-Q02::
High-risk patients often benefit from\: {
~Less attention
=Closer monitoring, proactive coordination, and individualized planning
~No care plan
~Standardized generic care
#### High-risk patients benefit from closer monitoring and individualized, proactive coordination.
}

// question: BRN-M09-Q03
::BRN-M09-Q03::
Geriatric patients may require special attention to\: {
~No special factors
=Polypharmacy, fall risk, cognitive changes, and functional status
~Only their age
~Marketing preferences
#### Geriatric care attends to polypharmacy, falls, cognition, and function.
}

// question: BRN-M09-Q04
::BRN-M09-Q04::
Polypharmacy can increase the risk of adverse drug events, especially in older adults. {T
#### Polypharmacy raises adverse-event risk, particularly in older adults. Confirm clinical specifics with SME.}

// question: BRN-M09-Q05
::BRN-M09-Q05::
Patient self-management education for chronic disease aims to\: {
~Make the patient dependent
=Build the patient's knowledge, skills, and confidence to manage their condition
~Replace all professional care
~Avoid the patient's involvement
#### Self-management education builds patient knowledge, skills, and confidence.
}

// question: BRN-M09-Q06
::BRN-M09-Q06::
Recognizing early warning signs of decompensation in a chronic condition allows the case manager to\: {
~Wait for a crisis
=Intervene or escalate early to prevent deterioration or hospitalization
~Ignore changes
~Stop monitoring
#### Early recognition supports timely intervention/escalation to prevent deterioration.
}

// question: BRN-M09-Q07
::BRN-M09-Q07::
Scenario\: A home-health patient with heart failure reports rapid weight gain and increased shortness of breath. The case manager should\: {
~Wait until the next routine visit
=Recognize possible decompensation, follow protocol, notify the appropriate provider promptly, and document
~Tell the patient it is normal
~Discontinue services
#### These are possible decompensation signs warranting prompt provider notification per protocol. (Clinical thresholds require SME confirmation.)
}

// question: BRN-M09-Q08
::BRN-M09-Q08::
Which support high-risk/chronic care management? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Individualized care planning
~%33.33333%Patient self-management education
~%-100.0%Ignoring comorbidities
~%33.33333%Proactive monitoring and coordination
}

// question: BRN-M09-Q09
::BRN-M09-Q09::
Addressing social determinants for high-risk patients can\: {
~Worsen outcomes
=Reduce barriers and improve the likelihood of successful self-management
~Be ignored safely
~Replace clinical care
#### Addressing social determinants reduces barriers and supports outcomes.
}

// question: BRN-M09-Q10
::BRN-M09-Q10::
Coordinating multiple specialists for a complex patient helps to\: {
~Fragment care
=Align treatment, reduce conflicting plans, and improve safety
~Increase duplication
~Confuse the patient
#### Coordination aligns specialists and reduces conflicting plans.
}

// question: BRN-M09-Q11
::BRN-M09-Q11::
Individualized goals and regular reassessment are important in managing chronic and high-risk patients. {T
#### Individualized goals and reassessment are key in chronic/high-risk management.}

// question: BRN-M09-Q12
::BRN-M09-Q12::
The overall aim of this module is to\: {
~Teach prescribing
=Strengthen management of chronic disease, geriatric, and high-risk patients
~Reduce monitoring
~Replace specialists
#### The aim is chronic, geriatric, and high-risk patient management.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/BRN/M10

// question: BRN-M10-Q01
::BRN-M10-Q01::
An integrated case-management approach means the case manager\: {
~Treats each issue in isolation
=Synthesizes assessment, planning, coordination, documentation, and advocacy into a cohesive process
~Focuses only on billing
~Avoids the team
#### Integrated case management synthesizes all core functions into a cohesive, patient-centered process.
}

// question: BRN-M10-Q02
::BRN-M10-Q02::
Applying the full case-management process to a complex patient begins with\: {
~Discharge
=Comprehensive assessment that informs an individualized plan
~Billing
~Marketing
#### The process begins with comprehensive assessment to inform an individualized plan.
}

// question: BRN-M10-Q03
::BRN-M10-Q03::
Across the case-management process, the patient's role should be\: {
~Excluded
=An active, informed partner throughout
~Limited to signing forms
~Replaced by family only
#### The patient is an active, informed partner throughout the process.
}

// question: BRN-M10-Q04
::BRN-M10-Q04::
Evaluating outcomes and revising the plan are ongoing parts of the case-management process. {T
#### Outcome evaluation and plan revision are continuous in case management.}

// question: BRN-M10-Q05
::BRN-M10-Q05::
When multiple priorities compete for a complex patient, the case manager should\: {
~Address them randomly
=Prioritize based on safety, acuity, and patient goals while coordinating the team
~Ignore safety
~Focus only on cost
#### Prioritization integrates safety, acuity, and patient goals with team coordination.
}

// question: BRN-M10-Q06
::BRN-M10-Q06::
Ethical and legal considerations in an integrated case should be\: {
~Ignored
=Woven throughout assessment, planning, communication, and documentation
~Considered only at discharge
~Left to others
#### Ethics and legal considerations are integral throughout the process.
}

// question: BRN-M10-Q07
::BRN-M10-Q07::
Scenario\: A complex home-health patient has a new chronic diagnosis, limited support, coverage questions, and a safety concern at home. An integrated response is to\: {
~Handle only the coverage issue
=Reassess holistically, update the plan, coordinate the team and resources, communicate in a payer-safe manner, address safety, and document thoroughly
~Discharge to simplify
~Focus only on documentation
#### Integrated management addresses clinical, social, coverage, safety, and documentation needs together.
}

// question: BRN-M10-Q08
::BRN-M10-Q08::
Which are integrated across a complete case-management episode? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Assessment and planning
~%33.33333%Coordination and advocacy
~%-100.0%Falsified documentation
~%33.33333%Evaluation and revision
}

// question: BRN-M10-Q09
::BRN-M10-Q09::
Demonstrating competency in this program is shown by\: {
~Memorizing terms only
=Applying the integrated process safely, ethically, and within scope to realistic scenarios
~Avoiding scenarios
~Ignoring documentation
#### Competency is shown by safe, ethical, in-scope application to realistic scenarios.
}

// question: BRN-M10-Q10
::BRN-M10-Q10::
Reflective practice at the end of a case helps the case manager to\: {
~Repeat mistakes
=Identify what worked, what to improve, and how to strengthen future practice
~Avoid learning
~Blame the patient
#### Reflection supports continuous improvement of practice.
}

// question: BRN-M10-Q11
::BRN-M10-Q11::
This 30-contact-hour program prepares RNs to apply integrated case-management skills; it does not certify a specialty or expand scope of practice. {T
#### The program builds skills via continuing education; it makes no certification or scope-expansion claim.}

// question: BRN-M10-Q12
::BRN-M10-Q12::
The capstone module's overall aim is to\: {
~Introduce new unrelated content
=Integrate and apply the full case-management process across realistic scenarios
~Replace prior modules
~Focus only on theory
#### The capstone integrates and applies the full process.
}

$CATEGORY: $course$/BRN/CAPSTONE_FINAL

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q01
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q01::
The core purpose of RN case management is to\: {
~Replace the physician
=Coordinate and advocate for safe, patient-centered care across settings
~Cut costs regardless of quality
~Eliminate documentation
#### Case management coordinates and advocates for patient-centered care.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q02
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q02::
Acting within RN scope of practice means\: {
~Doing any requested task
=Practicing within legal/professional boundaries for RNs
~Practicing medicine independently
~Ignoring standards
#### Scope defines legal/professional boundaries.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q03
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q03::
This continuing education is measured in\: {
~CEUs
=Contact hours
~Academic credits
~Clinical rotations
#### BRN CE is measured in contact hours, not CEUs.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q04
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q04::
A comprehensive assessment includes\: {
~Only diagnosis
=Physical, functional, psychosocial, and environmental factors
~Only insurance
~Only age
#### Holistic assessment spans multiple domains.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q05
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q05::
A patient-centered care plan goal should be\: {
~Vague
=Specific, measurable, and aligned with the patient's priorities
~Decided without the patient
~Facility-focused only
#### SMART, patient-aligned goals support individualized care.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q06
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q06::
The patient should be involved in developing their care plan. {T
#### Patient involvement is central to patient-centered planning.}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q07
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q07::
Care coordination aims to make care\: {
~Fragmented
=Safe, continuous, and non-duplicative across the team and settings
~Siloed
~Less communicated
#### Coordination aligns the team for continuous, non-duplicative care.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q08
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q08::
Structured handoffs primarily help to\: {
~Lose information
=Transfer accurate information and reduce errors
~Slow care
~Avoid documentation
#### Structured handoffs reduce errors at transitions.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q09
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q09::
Legally sound documentation is\: {
~Vague and delayed
=Accurate, objective, timely, complete, and legible
~Opinion-based
~Altered without notation
#### Sound documentation is accurate, objective, timely, complete, legible.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q10
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q10::
Care that was not provided should never be charted as if it were done. {T
#### Documentation integrity prohibits charting care not provided.}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q11
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q11::
Informed consent requires\: {
~A signature without understanding
=Understandable disclosure of risks/benefits/alternatives and voluntary agreement
~Only benefits disclosed
~Coercion
#### Informed consent requires disclosure and voluntary agreement.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q12
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q12::
Respecting autonomy means\: {
~Deciding for the patient
=Honoring the patient's right to make informed decisions
~Withholding information
~Overriding refusals
#### Autonomy honors informed patient decisions.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q13
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q13::
Which are core ethical principles? (Select all that apply.) {
~%33.33333%Autonomy
~%33.33333%Beneficence/non-maleficence
~%-100.0%Deception
~%33.33333%Justice
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q14
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q14::
A safe transition of care requires\: {
~Speed only
=Accurate information transfer, a clear plan, and confirmed follow-up
~Less patient involvement
~No documentation
#### Safe transitions require information transfer, a plan, and follow-up.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q15
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q15::
Teach-back at discharge is used to\: {
~Lengthen the visit
=Confirm the patient understands instructions
~Replace written instructions
~Avoid education
#### Teach-back confirms understanding.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q16
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q16::
Medication reconciliation at transitions helps to\: {
~Increase errors
=Identify and resolve medication discrepancies
~Replace the pharmacist
~Avoid documentation
#### Reconciliation reduces medication errors.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q17
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q17::
Medical necessity refers to services that are\: {
~The most expensive
=Appropriate and required for the condition per accepted standards
~Optional conveniences
~Patient-requested regardless of need
#### Medical necessity is appropriate, required care per standards.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q18
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q18::
Misrepresenting a patient's condition to obtain authorization is unethical and may constitute fraud. {T
#### Misrepresentation for authorization is unethical and potentially fraudulent.}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q19
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q19::
Payer-safe communication means\: {
~Exaggerating need
=Communicating accurately and truthfully, supported by documentation
~Withholding information
~Guaranteeing coverage
#### Payer-safe communication is accurate and documentation-supported.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q20
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q20::
An incident report should be\: {
~A blame tool
=An objective, factual, timely safety record
~Optional
~Opinion-filled
#### Incident reports are objective, factual, timely, and safety-focused.
}

// question: BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q21
::BRN-CAPSTONE_FINAL-Q21::
Escalation means\: {
~Hiding a concern
=Promptly raising a concern to the appropriate level when needed
~Waiting indefinitely
~Solving everything alone
#### Escalation routes concerns to the right level promptly.
}

